    "active_lock_reason": null,
    "body": "Saw a case where a task tracker threw an exception in the closeFile callback, and the exception processing caused closeFile to be called again.  releaseWriter can release the writer without nulling it (or otherwise indicating it should not be used again) and releaseResources also calls closeFile on any existing writer.\r\n\r\nIdeally there should be only one place that calls closeFile on the trackers, and even if it throws the writer should be marked as unusable afterwards in case we try to cleanup again due to exceptions.  The handling of writer close and tracker callbacks should always be protected to avoid trying to use the writer again if an exception occurs.  See `releaseCurrentWriter` as an example.",
